Devolution CS Mwangi Kiunjuri has asked the opposition to stop politicising the drought and support the government's mitigation efforts.Kiunjuri said politics should take the back seat and that all Kenyans should unite to find solutions.&ldquo;Everybody in the world understands the climate changes causing what we are witnessing today. The opposition should not be like the hyena that follows an animal waiting for it die so it can devour its carcass,&rdquo; he said.The Cabinet Secretary said the opposition, led by Raila Odinga, has no agenda for Kenya only wants to see President Uhuru Kenyatta's government defeated.Kiunjuri said the opposition should stop claiming Jubilee has used funds for food on campaigns.He said Cord leaders do not recognise anything good the government does but should respect victims of drought who will die if the government does not intervene.The CS spoke at Withare village in Laikipia county where he launched a borehole on Saturday. The borehole, built at a cost of Sh7.8 million, will serve more than 1,000 residents.Read: Declare drought a national disaster, senator urgesLaikipia West MP Wachira Karani also criticised opposition leaders saying their Bomas rally showed they do no have a plan.He urged those who have not registered as voters to do so when the exercise begins on Monday.The National Drought Management Authority said it will monitor the drought and update the government regularly.Chairperson Agnes Ndetei said they have sunk boreholes and built dams to reduce the effects.Kiunjuri reported in October last year that more than 1.3 million Kenyans have been affected by drought.Kilifi, Kwale, Garissa, Wajir, Mandera, Isiolo and Samburu are some of the most affected counties.More on this: Over 1.3 million affected by drought, says KiunjuriAlso read: Agency warns drought could worsen, PS says there is enough food